To the Korean Film Council (KOFIC),

I am writing to bring to your attention a serious matter concerning the misuse of public funds by a Korean higher education institution that has direct implications for film education and industry sectors supported by KOFIC.

We have obtained compelling evidence that Dongguk University has been making fraudulent claims about international partnerships - with at least one Canadian university officially denying any relationship despite still being listed as a partner on Dongguk's website. This raises grave concerns about potential taxpayer fraud, as Korean universities receive substantial government funding based on their reported international partnerships and global standing.

This matter is relevant to KOFIC for several reasons:

1. Dongguk University's Film and Digital Media departments receive public funding for film industry education and events
2. These departments maintain relationships with various film festivals and KOFIC-supported programs
3. Beyond false partnership claims, several international partners are re-evaluating relationships with Dongguk due to Title IX sexual violence risks
4. As this investigation expands, KOFIC-supported projects or events connected to Dongguk could come under scrutiny

Our campaign has already gained traction, with an X (Twitter) post exceeding 160 views and growing, which has tagged the Ministry of Education (@moefkorea_eng, @our_moe), National Research Foundation (@nrf_sns), and Citizens' Coalition for Educational Integrity (@kcleanedu). We have also informed various film-related institutions, including the Jeonju International Film Festival.

As the primary organization responsible for transparency in public funding for Korea's film industry and ethical standards in film education, we request that KOFIC investigate this issue and its implications for film programs and initiatives connected to Dongguk University.

